answers.body_markdown:
Unless you have disabled RTTI, `typeid` and `std::type_index` is the most reliable way to get a unique id for a type. Consider using it since unless explicitly disabled for the whole project, you already pay the full price for it.

---

If you insist on rolling your own solution, I&#39;d say the first one is better since the second don&#39;t compile and don&#39;t work.

That is because of this line:

    static const size_t Identifier = SCounter::Counter++;

First, you cannot have static data inside constexpr functions, and second you cannot use `Counter` which is not `constexpr` itself.

---

The first solution can be further improved. Instsead of having a pointer to `T`, which takes 8 bytes on a 64 bit system, you can have a smaller data that takes only 1 byte:

    template&lt;typename T&gt;
    struct TTypeIdentifier {
        static constexpr void const* GetIdentifier()
        {
            return &amp;Identifier;
        }

    private:
        struct id_t {};
        static constexpr id_t Identifier = id_t{};
    };

Using `id_t` is much smaller than a null pointer.

The only downside here is you cannot have predictable values and they are not arithmetic. You cannot compare them without using `std::less` or other function object given by the standard library. Any other comparator won&#39;t work.

